[2025-01-12 16:17:23] ASSISTANT: The term "Mahfuz" (محفوظ) in Arabic means "protected" or "guarded." It is often used in an Islamic context to refer to something that is preserved or safeguarded by Allah. One of the most common uses of the term is in reference to "Al-Lawh Al-Mahfuz" (اللوح المحفوظ), which means "The Preserved Tablet." According to Islamic belief, this is the divine record in which Allah has inscribed everything that has happened and will happen in the universe.

The concept of "Al-Lawh Al-Mahfuz" is derived from the Quran, where it is mentioned that everything is recorded in a "clear book" or "preserved tablet." For example, in Surah Al-Buruj, Allah says:

بَلْ هُوَ قُرْآنٌ مَّجِيدٌ {21} فِي لَوْحٍ مَّحْفُوظٍ {22}

"Nay, this is a glorious Quran, (inscribed) in a Tablet Preserved" (Quran 85:21-22).

This highlights the belief that Allah's knowledge and decrees are eternally protected and beyond alteration.
